What the Client Sees:

When your Spring controller returns a ResponseEntity, the client receives:

HTTP Status Code:

Example: 200 OK, 201 Created, 404 Not Found

Response Headers
Example:

X-Custom-Header: CustomValue
Content-Type: application/json

Response Body
Example (JSON):

{
  "id": 1,
  "name": "Alice",
  "email": "alice@example.com"
}

Example: GET /users/1
Suppose your controller returns:

return ResponseEntity.ok()
    .header("X-Custom-Header", "CustomValue")
    .body(user);

In Postman or curl, you’ll see:

Status:
200 OK

Headers:

X-Custom-Header: CustomValue
Content-Type: application/json

Body:

{
  "id": 1,
  "name": "Alice",
  "email": "alice@example.com"
}

Example: User Not Found

If your controller returns:
return ResponseEntity.notFound().build();

Status:
404 Not Found

Headers:

Content-Length: 0

Body:
(empty)

Example: POST /users
If your controller returns:

return ResponseEntity.status(HttpStatus.CREATED).body(createdUser);

Status:
201 Created
Headers:

Content-Type: application/json

Body:

{
  "id": 2,
  "name": "Bob",
  "email": "bob@example.com"
}

Summary

(i) The client sees the status code, headers, and body exactly as you set them in
 ResponseEntity.
(ii) Custom headers are visible in the response headers section.
(iii) The body is shown as JSON (or XML) in the response body.
(iv) Status codes help the client know if the request was successful, failed, or created
something new.

This is how ResponseEntity gives you full control over what the client receives [1] [2].



Q.What are Headers?

Headers in HTTP responses (and requests) are key-value pairs that provide extra information
about the communication between the client and server. They are not part of the main data
(body), but help both sides understand how to handle the data, connection, or request.

What Do Headers Indicate?
Metadata about the response or request:
Headers can describe the content type, length, encoding, authentication, caching, and more.

How to process the body:
For example, Content-Type: application/json tells the client that the body is JSON.

Control behavior:
Headers can instruct the client or server to cache, redirect, or authenticate.

Common Response Headers

Content-Type:
Indicates the format of the response body (e.g., JSON, XML, HTML).
Content-Type: application/json

Content-Length:
Size of the response body in bytes.
Content-Length: 123

Location:
Used in 201 Created responses to show where the new resource is.
Location: /users/2

Custom Headers:
You can add your own headers for extra info.
X-Custom-Header: CustomValue

Cache-Control:
Tells the client how to cache the response.
Cache-Control: no-cache


Why Are Headers Important?
(i)   They help clients and servers understand how to handle the data.
(ii)  They can carry authentication tokens, session info, or custom metadata.
(iii) They make APIs more flexible and robust.

In summary:
Headers are like labels or instructions attached to your HTTP messages, helping both sides
communicate more effectively
